sues**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to address the method issue since it seems impossible to use the actual add method for coverage. I wonder if creating my own class named com.google.protobuf.ExtensionRegistry is feasible, but I can't use the same package. Alternatively, I could add a dependency for protobuf-java using `testImplementation` instead of `compileOnly`, which lets me control the classpath. However, this might lead to duplicate classes. Still, if I can arrange the classpath order to prioritize protobuf-java before javalite, I might get the desired outcome. It's a bit tangled, but I’ll navigate through it.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing registry expectations**\\n\\nI’m considering that the test expected a full registry, so perhaps the previous passing builds had already included the protobuf-java dependency. If the tests had the FULL_REGISTRY_CLASS_NAME and passed before, that might mean the full registry was indeed available at some point. The test seems to only call newInstance or getEmptyRegistry, and in the failure case, the registry class is still considered full. This could mean that there’s an oversight in how the dependencies are configured or managed.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_XOZsxtbYTKALcJ0qCTKfRLoU|fc_00d63748e8d224170169f2d66340c08195b5bd41bbe4cfb282", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1 -type f -name '*.jar' | while read j; do if jar tf \"$j\" 2>/dev/null | grep -q '^com/google/protobuf/ExtensionRegistry.class$'; then echo \"$j\"; javap -classpath \"$j\" com.google.protobuf.ExtensionRegistry 2>/dev/null | grep 'public void add(com.google.protobuf.Extension' || echo '  no add Extension'; fi; done | head -100", "timeout": 60}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 806, "output": 720, "cacheRead": 33792, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 35318, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "tota